Excel analysis¶

Firstly I did Excel analysis in which columns such as cement, slag, ash and age has high range which means mix of gaussaian which can lead to outliers. Also after looking I also found that the data has no missing values and each attribute is of numerical type

STEPS:

  1. EDA : This step includes importing data, understanding data, descriptive analysis, visual analyisi ,cleaning data, treating outliers by repalcing them with median.
  2. Iteration 1 : This includes spliting data and scaling data then making linear regression, svm, decision tree on it.
  3. Iteration 2 : This includes only those column which are important and dropiing useless column as shown from pairlot and decision tree imp column faeture then making linear regression, svm, decision tree on it.
  4. Featurization : Techniques such as PCA and KPCA is used in this step
  5. Cluster ananlysis: As seen from pairplot their can be mix of gaussian therefore seeing or predicting clusterwise.
  6. Regularization : Tech such as ridge, lasso and elastic net are used in this step to see coeff magnitue if they are strong predictor or not
  7. Ensemble tech : I did ensemble using DT, Linear regression and SVR. In ensemble tech I used Bagging, Boosting, Random Forest and Xtreme forest. I also made ensemble on ensemble model where my meta model is SVR
  8. Model tuning : This is final step which includes random search to give model final push thus increasing accuracy

NOTE: I have replaced the outliers with median value as removing outliers will reduce our dataset and we will lose lots of valuable information in other columns as all independent columns are weak predictors but together they are stong predictors. Down the line after boxplot you will see I have provided two choice whether to remove outliers or replace outliers.

NOTE:¶

I have knowningly used X and y split, Scaling X and y and Splitting X and y to train and test before every Steps mentioned above. This is done so that I can change data at will also to not effect upcoming or previous steps

    k=int(k)
    print(i , " = " , k)

#quartile difference to see skewness
print("To see right or left side skew \n")   
for j,i in enumerate(col):
    k1= df[i].quantile(0.50) - df[i].quantile(0.75)
    k2= df[i].quantile(0.25) - df[i].quantile(0.50)
    if(abs(k1)>abs(k2)):
        print(j+1,i,": right side skew with right side being {0:.3f}".format(abs(k1)-abs(k2)), "more")
    else:
        print(j+1,i,": left side skew with left side being {0:.3f}".format(abs(k2)-abs(k1)), "more")

After seeing pairplot Diagonal: There are lots of cases of mix of gaussian column such as age, fineagg, coarseagg, water, slag, ash, superplastic this may result in making different model for different cases, also it can lead to outliers Number of cluster = 3*3=9 therefore 2 to 9. Also target column has normal distribution but no other column which signifies skweness Columns such as age, superplastic, water, ash, slag have outliers this will be more clear when doing boxplots

Offdiagonal: Each independent column are weak predictors of strength but they may together contribute to be great predictors. Also columns such as (slag and cement) and (slag and ash) shows little bit of correlation this will be more clear when doing corr()

5. Cluster Analysis¶

As seen in pairplot before, we have high cases of mix of gaussian herefore cluster analysis is very imp Here I started with elbow plot first which showed us number cluster that explain most of the variance. I selected 4,5,6 cluster and saw boxplot if each cluster is seperate or not.

In [1240]:
#Import all data 
df2=df.iloc[:,0:-1]
df2_scaled=df2.apply(zscore)## Identifying and handling outliers
In [1241]:
cluster_range = range( 2, 16 )   # expect 3 to four clusters from the pair panel visual inspection hence restricting from 2 to 6
cluster_errors = []
for num_clusters in cluster_range:
  clusters = KMeans( num_clusters, n_init = 5)
  clusters.fit(df2_scaled)
  labels = clusters.labels_
  centroids = clusters.cluster_centers_
  cluster_errors.append( clusters.inertia_ )
clusters_df = pd.DataFrame( { "num_clusters":cluster_range, "cluster_errors": cluster_errors } )
clusters_df[0:15]

In [1242]:
#Finding optimal no. of clusters
from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist
clusters=range(1,10)
meanDistortions=[]

for k in clusters:
    model=KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(df2_scaled)
    prediction=model.predict(df2_scaled)
    meanDistortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(df2_scaled, model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) / df2_scaled.shape[0])


plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Average distortion')
plt.title('Selecting k with the Elbow Method')
Out[1242]:
Text(0.5,1,'Selecting k with the Elbow Method')

7. Ensemble Tech¶

Here I used bagging, gradrient boost, adaboost, random forest and xtreme forest Further I have used bagging and adaboost boosting in SVR and linear Regression

Random searchcv¶

In [1298]:
from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV
rfTree = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=50, random_state=1)
In [1299]:
# Number of trees in random forest
n_estimators = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(start = 10 , stop = 15, num = 2)]   # returns evenly spaced 10 numbers
# Number of features to consider at every split
max_features = ['auto', 'log2']
# Maximum number of levels in tree
max_depth = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(5, 10, num = 2)]  # returns evenly spaced numbers can be changed to any
max_depth.append(None)
# Minimum number of samples required to split a node
min_samples_split = [2, 5, 10]
# Minimum number of samples required at each leaf node
min_samples_leaf = [1, 2, 4]
# Method of selecting samples for training each tree
bootstrap = [True, False]

# Create the random grid
random_grid = {'n_estimators': n_estimators,
               'max_features': max_features,
               'max_depth': max_depth,
               'min_samples_split': min_samples_split,
               'min_samples_leaf': min_samples_leaf,
               'bootstrap': bootstrap}

print(random_grid)

{'n_estimators': [10, 15], 'max_features': ['auto', 'log2'], 'max_depth': [5, 10, None], 'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10], 'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 4], 'bootstrap': [True, False]}
In [1300]:
# Use the random grid to search for best hyperparameters

# Random search of parameters, using 3 fold cross validation, 
# search across 100 different combinations, and use all available cores
rf_random = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=rfTree, param_distributions=random_grid,
                              n_iter = 5, scoring='neg_mean_absolute_error', 
                              cv = 5, verbose=2, random_state=1, n_jobs=-1,
                              return_train_score=True)

# Fit the random search model
rf_random.fit(X_train, y_train);

CONCLUSION:¶

As seen from the start i.e excel analysis the data suffered from outliers and mix of gaussian it was not easy to select appropriate technique also from various techniques it was evident that each attribute is a weak predictors. I have applied various techniques such as clustering, featurization and Regularization but none of them worked, but after applying Ensemble tech I got better results further using random forest I get best score. Also I used random forest for further tuming the model and in production I would use random forest. The confidence interval range for exact 95% is 94.3% to 83.7%
